<title>How the brother of the maiden taken up in a whirlwind became the Porcupine; followed by various remarks about porcupines</title>
<summary><i>The Young man (of the early race) who was changed into a porcupine. He is said to be the brother of the girl in the preceding legend. Remarks regarding the porcupine follow. In the Katkop dialect, by Díä!kwãin (L V.-13. 5023-5039, and 14. 5040-5054).</i> A tale of the Early Race (or !khwe ||na ss&apos;e !k&apos;e) in which the brother of the maiden taken up in a whirlwind by the angry Rain is transformed into a Porcupine. Parents tell their children to avoid eating the back of the porcupine&apos;s neck and tail, because that is where the hail sits. Also about porcupines and the stars. </summary><comments>1) p.5022v: this story was told to Dia!kwain by his mother (≠kamme-an), 2) p.5043v: what people call the place where they see the sun (&apos;ostrich eye&apos; or <i>Ttoi tsa xau</i>), 3) See also T<i>he maiden who was taken up in a whirlwind by the agency of the angry Rain and became a great snake</i>, 4) This story is found in Books V-13 and V-14</comments><date>19 July 1875 (started)</date><storypages>5023-5039, 5040-5054</storypages><category>The Rain and Rain&apos;s water</category><category>Transformation</category><category>Plants and animals</category><category>Custom and daily life</category><author>Dia!kwain (David Hoesar) (V)</author><keyword><kw>porcupine</kw><subkw>its nature and habits</subkw></keyword>
